Published: 21 August 2025

PyrogeographyFlames before summer
                    Graham Simpkins1

Nature Reviews Earth & Environment

(2025)Cite this article

Subjects

            AttributionClimate change

Access through your institution







                        Buy or subscribe

California has witnessed an increasing number of large and destructive wildfires, causing loss of life and substantial economic damage. Depending on the location, fires typically start in early summer. Yet there are suggestions that the fire season is lengthening, the drivers of which are unknown — fuel availability, ignition and climate could all contribute.This clear attribution to anthropogenic warming suggests that ongoing climate change will continue to push the fire season earlier in the year. In combination with an expected later end date to the fire season, wildfire could become a year-round hazard in California. Although such an extension might not increase damage, it does increase risk, highlighting the need for continued community preparedness, management and adaptation.



